1
00:00:34,350 --> 00:00:36,045
Hazy sunshine through Wednesday.

2
00:00:36,119 --> 00:00:40,749
And that's the 2:00 a.m. report.
You're listening to KMPC 710 in LA.

3
00:00:50,200 --> 00:00:55,331
The Mutual Broadcasting System presents
the Larry King Show...

4
00:00:55,705 --> 00:01:00,870
...network radio's most listened-to
talk program. And now, Larry King!

5
00:01:00,977 --> 00:01:04,435
We're with Rex Reed,
film critic of the New York Post.

6
00:01:05,849 --> 00:01:08,647
Give me the modus operandi of Rex Reed.

7
00:01:09,052 --> 00:01:12,215
Would you rather watch a movie
in a crowded theater...

8
00:01:12,288 --> 00:01:14,756
...or in that special screening room?

9
00:01:14,958 --> 00:01:17,392
I like to see movies in the daytime.

10
00:01:17,460 --> 00:01:21,487
I don't like to see movies at night
because I like to be fresh.

11
00:01:21,698 --> 00:01:24,189
I like 10:00 a.m. screenings if possible.

12
00:01:24,334 --> 00:01:28,896
I like to be in a screening room preferably
all alone. Although that rarely happens.

13
00:01:29,172 --> 00:01:33,165
I don't like to go to these
packed movie houses at night...

14
00:01:33,576 --> 00:01:38,604
... where they fill the theater with
all the secretaries from the film company...

15
00:01:38,681 --> 00:01:41,741
...and all the secretaries' second cousins...

16
00:01:42,218 --> 00:01:45,085
...because they want the audience
to scream and yell.

17
00:01:45,155 --> 00:01:47,851
They're like backers at an opening night.

18
00:01:47,924 --> 00:01:52,793
But what about that which Mel Brooks
told me, always needs an audience:

19
00:01:53,029 --> 00:01:56,294
The comedy?
If you're sitting alone at 10:00...

20
00:01:56,566 --> 00:01:59,694
-... watching a comedy--
-If it's really funny, I'll laugh.

21
00:01:59,769 --> 00:02:03,705
I don't need 40 other people laughing
to remind me I should be laughing.

22
00:02:03,807 --> 00:02:08,801
I mean, I don't respond very well
to mass hysteria anyway.

23
00:02:09,212 --> 00:02:12,409
With Rex Reed, we're ready to go
to your phone calls.

24
00:02:12,515 --> 00:02:14,608
We start with Cincinnati. Hello.

25
00:02:14,717 --> 00:02:16,241
Hi. Good morning, Larry.

26
00:02:16,319 --> 00:02:20,346
Rex, I wanted to tell you
that I think your forth rightness...

27
00:02:20,557 --> 00:02:25,460
...is refreshing and your dry wit
and your humor, it cracks me up.

28
00:02:26,162 --> 00:02:29,461
I like your opinions.
You usually agree with me.

29
00:02:29,632 --> 00:02:32,294
It gets me into a lot of trouble
sometimes, though.

30
00:02:32,936 --> 00:02:34,528
But do you care?

31
00:02:34,671 --> 00:02:36,969
-Well, I used to a lot.
-Really?

32
00:02:37,974 --> 00:02:41,375
I go back to, like today, I can go and see....

33
00:02:41,444 --> 00:02:44,242
I'll let myself see a "P" or a "PG"...

34
00:02:44,714 --> 00:02:47,979
...because I don't like to be
uncomfortable or embarrassed.

35
00:02:48,318 --> 00:02:51,617
I saw The Black Stallion twice,
so you know where I'm coming from.

36
00:02:51,688 --> 00:02:52,985
What's the question?

37
00:02:53,056 --> 00:02:56,025
Sex, to me, is not a spectator sport.

38
00:02:56,292 --> 00:03:00,729
Are we going to see some good,
thoughtful, clean movies again?

39
00:03:01,731 --> 00:03:03,562
You've had a few lately.

40
00:03:03,666 --> 00:03:08,103
I agree with you. The imagination can do
so much more to build a scene...

41
00:03:08,238 --> 00:03:10,399
...or to sustain an emotion.

42
00:03:10,506 --> 00:03:14,101
I found a lot of the pictures
that I saw, growing up...

43
00:03:14,210 --> 00:03:17,338
...much sexier than any of the things
I've seen today.

44
00:03:17,480 --> 00:03:21,712
I remember The Fountainhead
with Gary Cooper and Patricia Neal....

45
00:03:22,118 --> 00:03:23,176
Linda?

46
00:03:23,820 --> 00:03:27,221
She just looked at him.
You saw lust written all over her face...

47
00:03:27,290 --> 00:03:29,724
...and they didn't take
their clothes off at all.

48
00:03:30,260 --> 00:03:31,750
Are you sleeping?

49
00:03:33,496 --> 00:03:35,327
Maybe we shouldn't move.

50
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:39,195
Oh, God. What's the matter now?

51
00:03:39,636 --> 00:03:41,797
Nothing. It's just time
to ask these questions.

52
00:03:41,871 --> 00:03:45,568
We sold our house. We should have asked
these questions before.

53
00:03:46,209 --> 00:03:48,677
All right, then I can't talk to you,
so good night.

54
00:03:48,745 --> 00:03:51,509
Stop it!
You're just nervous about tomorrow.

55
00:03:51,648 --> 00:03:56,312
You'll get the promotion. We'll move into
the new house and we'll be happy. Okay?

56
00:03:56,920 --> 00:04:00,617
You should hear your voice.
It just fills this room with excitement.

57
00:04:00,823 --> 00:04:03,257
I'm tired. Stop questioning.

58
00:04:03,593 --> 00:04:06,426
We made a wise decision.
Let's feel good about it.

59
00:04:06,496 --> 00:04:08,396
All right. Okay, good night.

60
00:04:08,731 --> 00:04:10,198
Good night.

61
00:04:13,603 --> 00:04:14,729
Why that house?

62
00:04:15,672 --> 00:04:16,639
What?

63
00:04:16,773 --> 00:04:21,107
It's too close.
Maybe we should have moved far away.

64
00:04:21,511 --> 00:04:24,105
We needed more space,
and that house has more space.

65
00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:27,911
The purpose of a house is more than space.
We could've rented a locker.

66
00:04:28,651 --> 00:04:30,812
Also, we didn't get a tennis court.

67
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:32,417
We don't play tennis.

68
00:04:32,588 --> 00:04:35,421
We don't have a court.
If you have a court, you learn.

69
00:04:35,491 --> 00:04:38,949
Possibly some day we'll have a court
and we'll learn.

70
00:04:43,766 --> 00:04:46,200
-Can I ask you something else?
-What?

71
00:04:47,971 --> 00:04:50,667
How come we let the moving company
pack for us?

72
00:04:51,407 --> 00:04:54,740
Shouldn't we have done it ourselves?
Maybe we're being irresponsible.

73
00:04:54,811 --> 00:04:57,609
I don't believe you.
One minute it's a tennis court...

74
00:04:57,747 --> 00:05:01,183
...then you're worried about
the moving company packing a box.

75
00:05:01,684 --> 00:05:04,676
Sometimes I wish we were
a little more irresponsible.

76
00:05:04,754 --> 00:05:06,221
What does that mean?

77
00:05:06,289 --> 00:05:08,883
Nothing. Just get some sleep.
You'll feel better.

78
00:05:08,958 --> 00:05:13,918
What do you mean, you wish we were
irresponsible? Are we too responsible?

79
00:05:14,097 --> 00:05:16,793
Sometimes I think
we are a bit too controlled.

80
00:05:17,767 --> 00:05:19,860
You do? We're too "controlled"?

81
00:05:20,236 --> 00:05:23,069
How do you go out
and buy a $450,000 house...

82
00:05:23,339 --> 00:05:27,503
...and get all the things you want
and not be controlled?

83
00:05:28,177 --> 00:05:29,644
What are you talking about?

84
00:05:29,712 --> 00:05:32,613
What difference does it make?
I'll go sleep in the garage.

85
00:05:33,016 --> 00:05:34,984
-Don't do that!
-Why not?

86
00:05:35,084 --> 00:05:37,609
I'm responsible.
I should be guarding the car.

87
00:05:37,687 --> 00:05:38,984
You're insane!

88
00:05:40,456 --> 00:05:44,483
I'm insane and responsible.
This is a potent combination.

89
00:05:47,730 --> 00:05:49,357
I'm not sleeping in the garage.

90
00:05:49,432 --> 00:05:51,059
What am I doing? I'm not an animal.

91
00:05:51,134 --> 00:05:52,965
-What?
-I'm not an animal.

92
00:05:54,003 --> 00:05:56,164
Come on, come to bed.

93
00:05:57,340 --> 00:05:58,830
I apologize.

94
00:05:59,442 --> 00:06:01,137
But don't call me names.

95
00:06:01,511 --> 00:06:02,603
What names?

96
00:06:02,945 --> 00:06:07,575
Calling me responsible is calling me what?
Old or stodgy or stuffed up?

97
00:06:07,884 --> 00:06:10,546
I'm doing the best I can.
I don't know what else to do.

98
00:06:10,620 --> 00:06:14,056
Also, you're not so irresponsible yourself.
Look at your job.

99
00:06:14,157 --> 00:06:16,682
Personnel Director is like in a Nazi camp.

100
00:06:16,759 --> 00:06:20,092
If you hire one person they don't like,
they fire you.

101
00:06:20,696 --> 00:06:23,665
You're upset. I'm sorry I used that word.

102
00:06:25,701 --> 00:06:29,467
After tomorrow, everything will be better.
I'm positive. Don't you think so?

103
00:06:29,906 --> 00:06:31,396
You always say that.

104
00:06:31,641 --> 00:06:36,305
Yeah, but for eight years it's been one way.
I've been this employee...

105
00:06:36,446 --> 00:06:39,472
...and then tomorrow,
I'll get this promotion and that's it.

106
00:06:39,882 --> 00:06:42,146
I'll have stock in this agency.

107
00:06:42,251 --> 00:06:45,743
That makes me responsible.
Genuinely responsible.

108
00:06:46,222 --> 00:06:50,420
Now I can be irresponsible.
I'm in a position of responsibility.

109
00:06:50,760 --> 00:06:52,284
Do you know what I mean?

110
00:06:52,862 --> 00:06:54,659
-Yeah, I guess so.
-Okay.

111
00:06:55,264 --> 00:06:56,629
Good night.

112
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:13,179
How are you?

113
00:07:13,950 --> 00:07:15,611
Well, I'm flattered.

114
00:07:19,388 --> 00:07:20,946
That's more!

115
00:07:22,291 --> 00:07:26,352
Come over to our new house
and we'll barbeque. Let's celebrate this.

116
00:07:28,831 --> 00:07:31,994
Ribs, fish, I don't care. Anything.

117
00:07:33,136 --> 00:07:34,603
Did you ever barbeque--

118
00:07:34,670 --> 00:07:36,228
-What are you doing?
-Nothing.

119
00:07:36,305 --> 00:07:39,331
I'm on my way to meet Mr. Taft.
Can you be there in 20 minutes?

120
00:07:39,408 --> 00:07:43,344
I can't pick tile out this morning.
It's the biggest day of my life!

121
00:07:43,412 --> 00:07:46,609
-We said we'd do this together.
-I can't do it.

122
00:07:46,682 --> 00:07:48,343
You're in the kitchen more than me.

123
00:07:48,417 --> 00:07:51,875
I don't think about anything in the kitchen.
It's your kitchen.

124
00:07:53,022 --> 00:07:54,683
-Now we're angry.
-No, I'm not.

125
00:07:54,757 --> 00:07:57,658
-Good luck and you'll get your promotion.
-Think about this.

126
00:07:58,394 --> 00:08:00,055
-Good luck.
-Okay.

127
00:08:04,634 --> 00:08:05,623
How are you?

128
00:08:48,177 --> 00:08:50,042
-Good morning, Sylvia.
-Good morning.

129
00:08:53,883 --> 00:08:55,544
Hi. Are you Bob?

130
00:08:55,851 --> 00:08:57,842
-Bob? No.
-Sorry.

131
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:13,901
Well, I thought it was rude.
Got to go. 'Bye.

132
00:09:14,770 --> 00:09:16,237
-Good morning.
-How are you?

133
00:09:16,305 --> 00:09:18,773
-Your meeting is in 25 minutes.
-I'm very nervous.

134
00:09:18,841 --> 00:09:20,672
-You look great.
-You do, too.

135
00:09:20,743 --> 00:09:23,507
No calls at all. I really want to be alone.

136
00:09:24,180 --> 00:09:26,171
Get me the Mercedes place.

137
00:10:08,924 --> 00:10:10,448
-Hi.
-Hi.

138
00:10:10,926 --> 00:10:11,688
So?

139
00:10:12,094 --> 00:10:13,959
-Is it beautiful?
-What?

140
00:10:14,463 --> 00:10:16,294
The kitchen. What does it look like?

141
00:10:16,365 --> 00:10:18,697
I chose an orange tile.

142
00:10:19,035 --> 00:10:20,866
-Orange.
-Yeah, burnt orange.

143
00:10:21,904 --> 00:10:23,064
Sounds pretty.

144
00:10:23,973 --> 00:10:25,998
Patty, would you close the door?

145
00:10:29,812 --> 00:10:30,904
What's the matter?

146
00:10:31,380 --> 00:10:33,143
I'm going to hate this house.

147
00:10:35,151 --> 00:10:36,618
What are you talking about?

148
00:10:36,752 --> 00:10:39,380
This morning, after the contractor left,
I was all alone.

149
00:10:39,455 --> 00:10:43,687
I sat in the middle of the living room floor.
I got so sad.

150
00:10:43,959 --> 00:10:46,951
A preview of the next ten years.
I just started shaking.

151
00:10:47,296 --> 00:10:51,733
I don't like anything anymore.
I don't like my life, my house, anything.

152
00:10:51,801 --> 00:10:52,859
What do you mean?

153
00:10:52,935 --> 00:10:57,838
Nothing's changing. I'm not. David's not.
We've just stopped. Life's just going by.

154
00:10:58,574 --> 00:11:00,303
He genuinely believes...

155
00:11:00,376 --> 00:11:03,072
...that this promotion
will change everything. But...

156
00:11:03,145 --> 00:11:06,171
...he believed that every single promotion
and it never does.

157
00:11:06,248 --> 00:11:08,148
Things are always the same.

158
00:11:08,517 --> 00:11:10,781
Maybe this time it will change.

159
00:11:11,620 --> 00:11:13,451
-And if it won't?
-Then it won't.

160
00:11:13,789 --> 00:11:16,656
Then you get divorced.
Do whatever you have to do.

161
00:11:19,095 --> 00:11:20,528
This is Hans. Hold on, please.

162
00:11:20,596 --> 00:11:22,860
I've been holding most of the morning.

163
00:11:26,502 --> 00:11:28,561
This is Hans.

164
00:11:28,904 --> 00:11:29,962
David Howard.

165
00:11:30,039 --> 00:11:32,599
-How are you, David?
-Okay. Listen.

166
00:11:33,876 --> 00:11:38,540
I'm closing in on a decision.
The beige is the best interior.

167
00:11:39,382 --> 00:11:42,283
I think with the dark brown, that's...

168
00:11:42,685 --> 00:11:45,279
-...the best combination.
-That's the most beautiful.

169
00:11:45,354 --> 00:11:47,288
All right, so tell me again...

170
00:11:47,423 --> 00:11:52,656
...everything: tax, license,
out the door, in my garage--

171
00:11:52,728 --> 00:11:56,892
I don't know where your garage is,
but it's $44,420.

172
00:11:58,667 --> 00:12:00,498
It's a lot of money for a car.

173
00:12:00,569 --> 00:12:02,594
It's not a car. It's a Mercedes--

174
00:12:02,671 --> 00:12:05,697
I know it's a Mercedes,
but it's still a lot of money.

175
00:12:05,808 --> 00:12:08,834
Maybe you shouldn't buy the car.
Get a Nova.

176
00:12:09,512 --> 00:12:13,676
There are no extras, right? At that price,
I shouldn't have to add anything.

177
00:12:13,783 --> 00:12:16,251
You just have to add leather.

178
00:12:17,486 --> 00:12:21,081
-lt doesn't come with leather?
-No, that's why I said you have to add it.

179
00:12:21,157 --> 00:12:24,320
-What's in there?
-It's called "Mercedes leather."

180
00:12:24,860 --> 00:12:26,020
What would that be?

181
00:12:26,095 --> 00:12:28,825
It's a thick vinyl. Beautiful seat.
I'd prefer that.

182
00:12:28,931 --> 00:12:31,900
-Let's call it "that" then.
-Beautiful, thick vinyl seat.

183
00:12:32,334 --> 00:12:34,768
Wouldn't you think
there'd be leather in there?

184
00:12:34,837 --> 00:12:37,328
If you buy the car, I'll put some shoes in it.

185
00:12:39,508 --> 00:12:41,476
All right. Thank you.

186
00:12:41,544 --> 00:12:43,375
I'll see you when? Tomorrow night?

187
00:12:43,446 --> 00:12:47,610
I don't know. I'll think about it.
Talk with my wife. It's a big decision.

188
00:12:47,783 --> 00:12:49,512
How about Friday morning?

189
00:12:49,685 --> 00:12:52,779
I can't commit to any day right now.
Certainly not this week.

190
00:12:52,855 --> 00:12:56,313
You'll lose the car. I have stars coming in.

191
00:12:56,525 --> 00:12:58,493
Let me just call you back, all right?

192
00:12:58,594 --> 00:13:01,256
Hold on a second. I'm being buzzed.

193
00:13:03,299 --> 00:13:05,460
It's time for your meeting.

194
00:13:07,870 --> 00:13:11,704
Hans is on the phone. He's coming in
for the kill. Want to help me out?

195
00:13:11,774 --> 00:13:12,866
Oh, no!

196
00:13:25,454 --> 00:13:26,921
He'll call you back.

197
00:13:27,022 --> 00:13:29,490
-Good luck, you got it.
-This is it.

198
00:13:30,059 --> 00:13:34,052
I understand, but it's really impossible
right now. I can call you....

199
00:13:56,752 --> 00:13:58,049
-Good morning.
-Hi.

200
00:13:58,354 --> 00:14:00,151
Go on in, he's expecting you.

201
00:14:00,956 --> 00:14:02,651
-Good luck.
-Thank you.

202
00:14:09,632 --> 00:14:12,624
Say hi to Brad Tooley.
Brad, David Howard.

203
00:14:14,370 --> 00:14:16,770
Brad just joined the agency in the East.

204
00:14:17,106 --> 00:14:21,042
One of the top men at Doyle Dane.
He's fantastic, we're lucky to get him.

205
00:14:21,143 --> 00:14:24,977
I've got two of the best men
in modern advertising right here.

206
00:14:26,448 --> 00:14:29,212
Brad was blown away by your stuff.

207
00:14:29,285 --> 00:14:31,185
-Right, Brad?
-Very impressive.

208
00:14:31,353 --> 00:14:34,584
The Knudsen campaign
was one of the best I've ever seen.

209
00:14:35,291 --> 00:14:36,349
Thank you.

210
00:14:36,425 --> 00:14:39,656
Brad has joined the agency
for a very special reason.

211
00:14:40,329 --> 00:14:41,990
We're going to get Ford.

212
00:14:43,365 --> 00:14:45,356
I can't believe it! Ford?

213
00:14:45,501 --> 00:14:46,798
Trucks, too.

214
00:14:47,503 --> 00:14:50,199
This makes us the biggest agency
in the world!

215
00:14:50,272 --> 00:14:52,263
Puts us at the top of the heap.

216
00:14:52,775 --> 00:14:56,609
I can't believe this.
What a week for us all! This is great!

217
00:14:57,813 --> 00:14:59,610
-Now, David--
-Don't say it.

218
00:14:59,682 --> 00:15:03,118
As Senior Vice President,
I'm here 24 hours a day. Don't worry.

219
00:15:03,185 --> 00:15:05,050
I'm yours. I'll live on this floor.

220
00:15:05,120 --> 00:15:07,782
You're much too valuable
to be Senior Vice President...

221
00:15:07,856 --> 00:15:10,791
...but I do want you to move to New York
and work under Brad.

222
00:15:10,859 --> 00:15:12,827
You two will be in charge of Ford.

223
00:15:12,995 --> 00:15:16,362
You're going to have to hurry though,
you start in two weeks.

224
00:15:16,432 --> 00:15:18,525
God, I'm sorry. I didn't hear....

225
00:15:18,634 --> 00:15:19,965
You start in two weeks.

226
00:15:20,035 --> 00:15:23,994
There was much too much information.
I'm Senior Vice President, then I got lost.

227
00:15:24,073 --> 00:15:26,906
No, I've hired Phil Shubano
as Senior Vice President.

228
00:15:27,743 --> 00:15:31,975
You couldn't. I don't understand.
I'm Senior Vice President.

229
00:15:32,414 --> 00:15:34,075
No, Phil Shubano is.

230
00:15:34,950 --> 00:15:36,281
Then what am l?

231
00:15:37,319 --> 00:15:39,310
He's giving you quite a compliment.

232
00:15:39,388 --> 00:15:42,789
I ask him for the best man he had
and he didn't hesitate for a moment.

233
00:15:44,393 --> 00:15:47,487
He didn't? I don't want to go to New York.

234
00:15:48,530 --> 00:15:53,297
I should get the position I deserve,
not be shifted to another account.

235
00:15:53,736 --> 00:15:56,671
"Another account"?
This is not just "another account."

236
00:15:56,772 --> 00:15:57,761
It's Ford.

237
00:15:57,840 --> 00:16:01,799
